<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Legacy Event Points
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Event Point types that appear to have been developed, prototyped, or retained in the file/editor format, but did not make the final active mission workflow.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        About Legacy Event Points
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Some Event Point types still appear in the editor even though they are not used by the final
        release mission workflow. These are best treated as <Bold>legacy</Bold>,
        <Bold>unused</Bold>, <Bold>scrapped</Bold>, or <Bold>partially implemented</Bold> mission
        features.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        They are documented here so that users understand what they are seeing in the Event Point
        list, but they should generally not be used when building a new playable mission unless you
        are deliberately testing old or unfinished behaviour.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Legacy Event Points may still appear in the editor, but that does not mean they are safe or useful for new missions.
                    Use active mission Event Points for normal objectives, triggers, NPCs, messages, counters, timers, and win/lose logic.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_legacy_eventpoints_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Legacy Event Point Reference
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Burn Prim</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Intended to set a prim/object on fire or change it to a burning state. This appears to be a
        legacy or special-case object interaction and is not part of the normal current mission
        workflow.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">AutoSave</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        At one point in development, automatic mission saving appears to have been planned. This was
        scrapped. AutoSave should not be used for new missions and should not be relied on for
        checkpoints, recovery, or mission progression.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Create Map Exit</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Appears to be an older or unused system for creating map exits or mission transition points.
        Modern mission flow should use the active mission completion and transition systems instead.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Target WayPoint</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Appears to be an old camera or target path waypoint type. In final mission editing, active
        camera, target, and waypoint logic should be used instead where applicable.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Cut Scene</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Intended for embedded cutscene data or scripted cinematic playback. This appears to be a
        legacy or unfinished path and is not recommended for new mission authoring unless specifically
        testing old cutscene support.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Teleport</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Intended as a teleport entry or activation point. It appears to be legacy or unfinished in the
        final mission workflow. Avoid relying on it for normal mission progression unless tested.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Teleport Target</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Intended as the paired destination for a Teleport Event Point. Like Teleport, this appears to
        be legacy/unfinished and should be treated with caution.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Shout</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Appears to relate to old shout/dialogue trigger behaviour. Modern mission dialogue should use
        the active message, conversation, radio, or text Event Points instead.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Create Bomb</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Intended to create a bomb or explosive object. It appears to be unused or special-case in the
        final release workflow. Use current supported trap, object, or mission hazard Event Points
        where available.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Interesting</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Likely a marker or debug/development Event Point used to mark a point of interest. It does
        not appear to be part of the normal final mission scripting workflow.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Dynamic Light</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Intended to create or control dynamic/animated light behaviour from mission data. Because
        light files and the Light Editor now handle normal map lighting, this Event Point should be
        treated as legacy/special-case unless deliberately testing dynamic light behaviour.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Go There Do This</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Appears to be an older high-level scripted instruction Event Point: send an actor somewhere
        and perform an action. It does not appear to be part of the reliable final mission workflow
        and should be avoided for new mission logic unless specifically tested.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Recommended Use
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        If you find these Event Points in an existing mission, leave a note explaining that they are
        legacy/unused unless testing proves otherwise. If you are creating a new mission, use the
        active Event Point types instead.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use active <Bold>Create Player</Bold>, <Bold>Create NPC</Bold>, <Bold>Create Creature</Bold>, <Bold>Create Item</Bold>, and <Bold>Objective</Bold> logic for normal mission setup.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold>, <Bold>Timer</Bold>, <Bold>Counter</Bold>, and <Bold>Radius</Bold> triggers for reliable mission sequencing.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use supported <Bold>Message</Bold>, <Bold>Conversation</Bold>, and <Bold>Nav Beacon</Bold> Event Points for player guidance.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use <Bold>End Game Win</Bold> and <Bold>End Game Lose</Bold> for final mission outcomes.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

</FlowDocument>
